{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:57:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:57:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17727"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17727"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72143"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10441"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17727"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57613"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10330"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24383"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72143"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following changes is commonly associated with chronic pain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced descending inhibitory responses","Decreased attentional focus on salient stimuli","Increased physiological responses to high pain levels","Improved pain tolerance over time","Enhanced ability to ignore pain"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic pain is known to alter the body\u0027s pain modulation systems. One such change is the \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced descending inhibitory responses\u003C/strong\u003E, which are part of the body\u0027s natural mechanism to suppress pain signals. This reduction can lead to increased pain perception and sensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContrary to the option, chronic pain often leads to \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased attentional focus\u003C/strong\u003E on pain-related stimuli, rather than decreased focus. Patients with chronic pain may find it difficult to divert their attention away from the pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic pain can also result in \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased physiological responses\u003C/strong\u003E to pain, such as heightened sensitivity or hyperalgesia, rather than improved pain tolerance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver time, chronic pain does not typically lead to \u003Cstrong\u003Eimproved pain tolerance\u003C/strong\u003E. Instead, it can cause a heightened sensitivity to pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic pain does not usually enhance the \u003Cstrong\u003Eability to ignore pain\u003C/strong\u003E. Instead, it often becomes more difficult for patients to manage and ignore the pain over time.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic pain can lead to reduced descending inhibitory responses, which are part of the body\u0027s natural pain modulation system.","Chronic pain often results in increased attentional focus on pain-related stimuli, rather than decreased focus.","Chronic pain can cause increased physiological responses to pain, such as heightened sensitivity or hyperalgesia."],"references":["May A. Chronic pain may change the structure of the brain. Pain. 2008 Jul;137(1):7-15. doi: 10.1016/j.pain.2008.02.034. Epub 2008 Apr 14. PMID: 18410991","Rodriguez-Raecke R, Niemeier A, Ihle K, Ruether W, May A. Structural brain changes in chronic pain reflect probably neither damage nor atrophy. PLoS One. 2013;8(2):e54475. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0054475. Epub 2013 Feb 6. PMID: 23405082; PMCID: PMC3566164","Yang S, Chang MC. Chronic Pain: Structural and Functional Changes in Brain Structures and Associated Negative Affective States. Int J Mol Sci. 2019 Jun 26;20(13):3130. doi: 10.3390/ijms20133130. PMID: 31248061; PMCID: PMC6650904","Crofford LJ. Chronic Pain: Where the Body Meets the Brain. Trans Am Clin Climatol Assoc. 2015;126:167-83. PMID: 26330672; PMCID: PMC4530716","Ren K, Dubner R. Interactions between the immune and nervous systems in pain. Nat Med. 2010 Nov;16(11):1267-76. doi: 10.1038/nm.2234. Epub 2010 Oct 14. PMID: 20948535; PMCID: PMC3077564."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57613"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17727"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57613"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T23:44:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T23:45:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10441"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72143"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":